related_questions.question: What is myrrh used for in the Bible?
related_questions.snippet: Myrrh was used in ancient Israelite temple worship as an ingredient in the holy anointing oil for consecrating priests, the tabernacle, and kings (see Exodus 30:23–25). It was used in the purification of Queen Esther (see Esther 2:12), and it was also used in embalming (see John 19:39).

related_questions.question: What did myrrh smell like?
related_questions.snippet: The scent of myrrh is complex and difficult to describe. It is often described as having a balsamic, slightly spicy and slightly smoky odor. Some people say it has a note of undergrowth or dried earth.

text_blocks.snippet: Myrrh is a fragrant, yellow resin that comes from the Commiphora tree, a small, thorny tree that is native to Africa and the Arabian Peninsula. The resin is extracted from cuts in the tree's bark. Myrrh has been used for thousands of years in medicine, perfumery, and incense.
Here are some things to know about myrrh:

list.title: Uses
list.snippet: People use myrrh for a variety of conditions, including back pain, diarrhea, parasite infections, and wound healing. However, there is little scientific evidence to support these uses.

list.title: Side effects
list.snippet: High doses of myrrh can cause severe heart irregularities. People with sensitive skin may develop an allergic reaction. Pregnant women should avoid taking myrrh by mouth.

list.title: Chemical composition
list.snippet: Myrrh is made up of 3–4% impurities, 7–17% volatile oils, 25–40% alcohol soluble resins, and 57–61% water soluble gum.

list.title: Smell
list.snippet: Myrrh has a warm, smoky, musky scent. Lindine, a foses perine, is one of the chemicals responsible for myrrh's smell.

answer_box.title: MYRRH - Uses, Side Effects, and More - WebMD
answer_box.snippet: Overview. Myrrh is a yellow, fragrant, sap-like resin that comes out of cuts in the bark of certain Commiphora trees, including the Commiphora myrrham tree. Myrrh contains chemicals that might reduce pain and kill bacteria. It's used worldwide but is especially popular in China and Egypt.
